The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Usha Martin earnings up 38%

 A STAFF REPORTER

 Usha Martin MD Rajeev Jhawar (left) with chairman B.K. Jhawar in Calcutta on Wednesday. A Telegraph picture

 Calcutta, July 25: Usha Martin has posted a 38 per cent growth in profit after tax for the first quarter of 2007-08 at Rs 37.68 crore against Rs 27.31 crore in the corresponding period last year.

 Net sales of the countrys leading producer of wire rope and speciality steel grew 8 per cent to Rs 503.76 crore from Rs 464.40 crore during the corresponding period last year. 

 Profit before tax rose to Rs 55.28 crore from Rs 35.18 crore, an increase of over 57 per cent.

 The captive consumption of steel for downstream value addition has registered a growth of over 19 per cent at 43,362mt compared with 36,323mt in the corresponding period last year.

 Rajeev Jhawar, managing director of the company, said the operating margin was expected to go up by 4 percentage points after the plants started using iron ore from captive mines. This would go up by another 4 percentage points when it starts using coal from its own mine that would come into production by the end of this year.

 As a result, its operating margin will reach 30 per cent.

 Prashant Jhawar, vice-chairman of the company, said all its expansion plans were on schedule and would be completed on time.

 It would have a 1-million-tonne speciality steel capacity, to be entirely fed by captive iron and coal.

 The company also recorded sales of 59,769 carbon credit, amounting to Rs 4.5 crore.

 The board of directors has decided to split the stock from Rs 5 to Re 1 per share.

 About the US wire plant, Bruton Shaw Americas Inc, Jhawar said it would start commercial production during the current quarter with a 6,000-tonne capacity in the first phase.




